Wash and dry all produce.

Finely dice @Roma tomato{1}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}. Halve @lime{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, scallions, a big squeeze of lime juice, and a
drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}. Core, deseed, and dice
@poblano pepper{1} into ½-inch pieces.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and
poblano; cook until just softened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tbsp}. Cook, stirring, until fragrant and warmed
through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Remove pan from heat.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add
@Old El Paso Refried Black Beans{16%ounce} and cook until warmed through,
~{1-2%minutes}. Reduce heat to low and stir in @butter{1%tbsp}.

Remove pot from heat. Season with plenty of salt and pepper.

Place @flour tortillas{6} on a clean work surface, then spread with beans.
Place a small amount of filling on one half of each tortilla, then sprinkle with
@pepper jack cheese{1/2%cup}.

Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create flautas. Place seam
sides down on a #plate{}.

Wash out pan used for filling. Heat a large drizzle of oil in same pan over
medium-high heat. Add flautas seam sides down.

Cook, carefully turning so flautas stay intact, until golden brown and crispy,
~{1-2%minutes} per side.

> Work in batches if necessary and watch carefully to avoid burning.

Divide flautas between plates and top with @guacamole{4%tbsp},
@pico de gallo{} prepared earlier, and @sour cream{4%tbsp}. Alternatively, serve
with toppings on the side.